A Toolkit for the Quantitative Analysis of Audiovisual Speech Data: @PUPolitics asst. prof. Dean Knox aims to develop a #machinelearning powered program to collect, clean and analyze audiovisual data in human speech, adding to the overall effectiveness of communication analysis.

Physical Priors for Generative Modeling of Molecular Structures and Interactions: @PrincetonCS prof. @ryan_p_adams and @PrincetonChem prof. Abigail Doyle plan to use #ML to model molecular structures and their chemical reactions in order to create new, useful compounds.

Towards Compositional Grounding of Language in Perception: @PrincetonCS faculty members Olga Russakovsky and @karthik_r_n will establish metrics to evaluate the accuracy of various image captioning systems and find methods to improve these systems.

Decoding the Language of the Brain: @HassonUri of @PsychPrinceton & @PrincetonNeuro and @karthik_r_n of @PrincetonCS's project aims to dive into the inner workings of the human brain and study how thoughts become words, how we communicate with each other, and our use of language.

Bayesian Optimization Approach to Experimental Design for Optobinder Synthesis: @BeEngelhardt of @PrincetonCS, Mengdi Wang of ORFE and @PrincetonMolBio's @toettch plan to use #machinelearning to model strategies that may make proteins more responsive for optogenetics.

Unveiling the History of the Milky Way Galaxy: Mariangela Lisanti of @PrincetonPhys aims to use machine learning techniques to study the data coming from a billion stars via the @ESAGaia satellite, launched in 2013, to shed light on the evolution of the Milky Way.

Secure & Private Federated Learning: @prateekmittal_ and H. Vincent Poor's project will use data science to look at security, privacy & utility issues in federated learning (a technique allowing computer programs to train from decentralized data) & design them to be more robust.

Society-Scale Behavioral Simulations Through Crowdsourcing: faculty members Tom Griffiths, @alinicoman, Simon Levin, @betsylevyp and @elkeweber plan to confront intertwined behavioral issues in online social networks that are impacting the global warming debate.

Seeking to Greatly Accelerate the Achievement of Quantum Many-body Optimal Control Through the Use of Artificial Neural Networks: @PrincetonChem prof. Herschel Rabitz seeks to design, model, understand & control quantum dynamics phenomena between different particles.

Thank you to @dr_yusefsalaam and @esglaude for this evening's discussion! – at McCosh 10
Before taking audience questions, @dr_yusefsalaam shows off his new necklace - which he designed himself - that says "Exonerated 5" around the edge.
"The beauty of being known about the 'Exonerated 5' ... it leaves no shadow of doubt." @dr_yusefsalaam tells @esglaude that it was @Oprah who gave the group that moniker.
Drawing on the words and experiences from Nelson Mandela and Maya Angelou, @dr_yusefsalaam says he isn't bitter about his wrongful imprisonment.

"Korey is the most necessary out of all of the 5. He was not a suspect. He got the most time. He received the most hell ... Korey is so special ... the truth came out because of Korey." @dr_yusefsalaam on his relationship with Korey Wise
"If you go to prison, you can do time or let time do you." @dr_yusefsalaam says that having his mind be free helped him get through his wrongful imprisonment
"As I got out around the world I can only thank god for having allowed me to grow through this in order to affect people's lives today in a way I could never imagine." @dr_yusefsalaam

Asking about #WhenTheySeeUs on @netflix, @esglaude wants to know how the film changed @dr_yusefsalaam's life. "@WhenTheySeeUs gave us the awesome opportunity to be on a global platform with tremendous responsibility."

"It wasn't an anomaly. This is business as usual ... our story is equally as important to be able to catapult us into where we need to be as a people." @dr_yusefsalaam on the Central Park jogger case.

"Has anyone ever planned to be dead or in jail by the age of 21?" @dr_yusefsalaam says that many have been taught that going to jail is a right of passage, but "no one talks about the hopelessness of prison."
"The true fight has never been white against black ... it's been that of spiritual wickedness in high and low places." @dr_yusefsalaam
"My mind was moved to write something. I never wrote this way before." @dr_yusefsalaam wrote a book of poems during his imprisonment, but reads "Them," written after he was released.
"This was a part of a process, a systemic issue that has been a founding fiber ... of this country." @dr_yusefsalaam on his wrongful imprisonment
"What I couldn't reconcile during the trial with was what cause them to look at me with such anger and hatred in their eyes." @dr_yusefsalaam on his experience during the trial.

"The beauty of what happened to me ... it caused me to come into this understanding very very early in life ... I was given the opportunity to live life without fear." @dr_yusefsalaam talks with @esglaude about his experience at 15 years old. – at McCosh 10

Tonight's talk gets started with a note about just how packed the room is. "I don't know if you can see, but you all look beautiful," says @dr_yusefsalaam while @esglaude takes a photo of the large crowd.

Thanks to this afternoon's panelists @KevinMKruse, Bill Keller, @AndrewChignell and @deborahamos and moderator @Joe_Stephens!

On utilizing librarians for media literacy... @KevinMKruse: "I teach history. Part of that is teaching students how to read a source." @AndrewChignell will incorporate them in his "Ethics of Food" course. @Joe_Stephens applauds those at @PULibrary who have assisted in classes.

Advice from @KevinMKruse on getting trustworthy news: "Part of it is to be mindful of what you consume ... not just clickbait ... but really put your money behind this ... support your local newspaper!" He continues, "Really think about what you consume & pay for what you want."

Agreeing with @KevinMKruse on the positive uses of social media, @deborahamos says, "There are so many stories I see [bubbling up] 2 days before they get to the mainstream media ... it's a tip sheet for all of us."

"Twitter does let you sample a variety of views," says @KevinMKruse, "to follow people who have a different perspective, especially in the news media ... I think it causes me to challenge some of my own assumptions in a healthy way."
With over 350K followers on Twitter, prof. @KevinMKruse knows a thing or two about the platform. "It's a great way that reporters can show their work."
"Do we need to worry about trust?" asks @Joe_Stephens. "There's a rigor in worrying which keeps you on your toes," answers @deborahamos. "Do we need to worry about mistrust?" rebuts Bill Keller.

"We are having this conversation in a post-truth world, and we may be in a post-trust world," says @deborahamos. She goes on to ask, "Do we need to redefine trust?" while noting that some polls about trust are confusing and poorly defined.

Ferris prof. of Journalism in Residence and international correspondent for @NPR @deborahamos says, "The media as a conglomerate simply does not exist ... 'Do I trust media?', I find, is just a false question ... Really what we're asking tonight is 'Is democracy in trouble?'"
Do we feel disappointed or do we feel betrayed when we realize there has been misinformation in the media? "It's unclear," says @andrewchignell.

Laurance S. Rockefeller Professor in Religion, Philosophy and the University Center for Human Values @AndrewChignell discusses what trust is and its many definitions and meanings - along with their vulnerabilities.

Keller goes on to provide some advice on how to change this "trust" crisis. "Identify your sources, own up to your mistakes ...Fact checking is important ... You need to pay attention to falsehoods." He also says there needs to be more media literacy classes in schools.

Next up is Bill Keller, Visiting McGraw Prof. Of Writing, former exec. Editor of @nytimes and founding Editor in Chief of the @MarshallProj. Keller says that some of the mistrust is on the audience, who "expect news reports to be short and uncomplicated" and entertaining.

When it comes to trusting the news media, @KevinMKruse adds, "I'm a historian ... I'm familiar with the long history of the conservative case against mainstream media." He gives a brief history of the last 50 years and how much trust people have put into the news media.
Starting off with the question, "Do you trust the news media?" Prof. @KevinMKruse's quick response? "Yes."
Director of the #PrincetonU Program in Journalism @Joe_Stephens starts off by noting the importance of discussions like today's "to keep democracy healthy and functioning."

In just a few short minutes we'll be tweeting live from this event, featuring panelists @KevinMKruse, @deborahamos, @MarshallProj founder Bill Keller, and @AndrewChignell and moderated by @Joe_Stephens. #PrincetonU

How can we solve water management problems? #PEI25 @water_futures: Pricing @Prof_FSultana: Water education research & water ethics @GeorgeHawkinsDC: Paying for #AI sensors in our sewer systems

"Do we really want that water to disappear? What will water systems look like? ... It's one of the grander challenges that we face." @JayFamiglietti notes that parts of the U.S. that grow produce are getting drier, a problem the country will have to face head-on. #PEI25

"What's fascinating to me," says @GeorgeHawkinsDC, is that "there's a blank spot for this gigantic public sector," noting there's room for water utilities to make a difference. He adds, "Water utilities are connected to everyone ... we connect to the people we serve." #PEI25

There's a connection between water inequality and social inequality, says @Prof_FSultana, adding, "At the same time, we're seeing these other issues at play ... we're trying to figure out how water injustices and climate injustices are interlinked." #PEI25

"Based on my work on conflict over water, it's a pretty hopeful story .. There is a lot of reason for hope. It's hard to do and there's a lot of complexities to doing it," says @water_futures, but cooperation over conflict is helping to make a difference. #PEI25

"The high latitudes and the low latitudes - the already wet areas of the world - are getting wetter ... In between, the already dry areas of the world are getting drier." @JayFamiglietti says these results were predicted for the end of the century, but are happening now. #PEI25
With a lively story about a flood he witnessed in Washington, D.C., former CEO & Manager of DC Water @GeorgeHawkinsDC emphasizes, "Climate change is here and the consequences are now." #PEI25
Having witnessed water poverty, "from a very young age I began to appreciate the importance of water ... in human life ... and how it influences how Earth functions," says @Prof_FSultana. #PEI25

Growing up playing soccer in Kentucky, @water_futures had a coach who was an environmental lawyer, which sparked his interest in climate at a young age. Through college and his career, he has realized the importance of water supply and its impact. #PEI25

"My job in the world is to help solve these really big challenges ... to provide ideas and frameworks and tools ... whatever's going to help companies get there." @AndrewWinston adds, "We have to solve those problems and work back from there." #PEI25

"My advice is not to aim for prizes or awards. We’re in this for the joy of research, the fascination, the love of science. … I remember being amazed that I could get paid for this." Professor Jim Peebles *62, winner of the 2019 @NobelPrize in Physics: http://bit.ly/2oio73l

Catch up with the @NobelPrize news and congratulatory messages for prof. emeritus and 1962 graduate alumnus James Peebles “Princeton professor emeritus wins Nobel in Physics” by @Princeton https://twitter.com/i/moments/1181562850365628416 #NobelPrize

Woken around 5:30am this morning, Prof. James Peebles *62 thought, "When you receive a phone call that early in the morning, it’s usually something horrible — or it’s this!” "This" ended up being a #NobelPrize: https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/10/08/joy-ride-career-peebles-wins-nobel-prize-physics-tackling-big-questions-about
A toast to Jim Peebles, who joins the ranks of fellow Princetonians Joe Taylor, Sir Angus Deaton and Duncan Haldane as a #NobelPrize Laureate!
"Now I know how rockstars feel." Richardson Auditorium gives a standing ovation for #NobelPrize winner James Peebles.
"I don't think you can imagine how good this makes me feel." #NobelPrize Laureate Jim Peebles sends appreciation to his colleagues and those who have reached out to send him congratulations.

"I hope you guys hurry up and make those discoveries so that I can enjoy them ... We're in this for the joy of research ... Don't judge yourself by the awards you've won." Prof. Jim Peebles, #NobelPrize Laureate, on advice for the next generation of cosmologists

"One of my earliest memories was throwing a tantrum because I couldn't put together the coffee percolator ... I love building things." #NobelPrize Laureate Jim Peebles talks about his early love for making things work
"Just a joy to see the recognition of work that so many have done." Prof. Peebles talks about how it feels winning the #NobelPrize
"Scientists like Jim are a very rare breed ... we are very proud to have him as our colleague." #NobelPrize

"It's a well deserved recognition for a great scientist and colleague ... he's one of the true pioneers of physical cosmology." Physics Department Chair Herman Verlinde begins his remarks about #NobelPrize Laureate Jim Peebles

"After serving as an instructor and researcher in the early 1960s, he became an assistant professor in 1965, an associate professor in 1968, and a full professor in 1972. He transferred to emeritus status in 2000." Peebles has spent his entire career at #PrincetonU. #NobelPrize

"While searching the cosmos, Jim never lost focus on what was right in front of him – his students ... And while he may—technically—be 'emeritus,' Professor Peebles has not stopped." Pres. Eisgruber reminds the audience that Peebles has a new book coming this spring. #NobelPrize

"He exemplifies both Princeton’s tradition of brilliant, path-breaking research in physics, cosmology, and gravitation, as well as this University’s commitment to put its best scholars in the classroom." #NobelPrize

"It is also a wonderful day for the University community—the students, faculty, and staff who are at once honored, humbled, just plain overjoyed to call Jim Peebles a teacher, a mentor, a colleague, and a friend." #NobelPrize

"Today is a special day for the Laureate, his family, and his countries – in this case, both Canada and the United States can beam proudly." Pres. Eisgruber begins his remarks at the press conference for #NobelPrize Laureate Jim Peebles

The stage is set for a press conference with #PrincetonU professor emeritus and 1962 graduate alumnus Jim Peebles who has been awarded the 2019 #NobelPrize in Physics "for theoretical discoveries in physical cosmology." Watch the livestream: http://mediacentrallive.princeton.edu/
#NobelPrize winner and professor emeritus Jim Peebles addresses colleagues, postdocs and students from @PrincetonPhys - "My best wish to you all is keep surprising me."
Professors Herman Verlinde, Stephen Boughn, @DavidSpergel and Andrew Appel share a moment with their colleague and the 2019 #NobelPrize winner in Physics, Jim Peebles.
The Department of Physics celebrating professor emeritus Jim Peebles on winning the #NobelPrize in Physics "for theoretical discoveries in physical cosmology." http://bit.ly/2p00axy

"We now have this story of how the universe came to be, from its earliest moments to the beautiful and rich cosmos around us today. Jim essentially wrote that story, making fundamental contributions to all of it." Prof. @j_dunkley congratulates #NobelPrize Laureate Jim Peebles – at Jadwin Hall - Dept. Of Physics

"I got into cosmology by the advice of Prof. Bob Dicke. I reluctantly started doing research and writing papers ... as I worked, the subject became more and more interesting ... I never stopped." Prof. Peebles on the early beginnings of his career #NobelPrize
"It's been a thrilling life ... I certainly have enjoyed teaching. You learn a lot when you teach a course." Prof. Peebles is even teaching this morning among press and #PrincetonU staff. #NobelPrize

"I do have a somewhat iconoclastic mind. That leads me to ask questions and to be skeptical about the answers. And, by being skeptical, that led to new directions." @NobelPrize Laureate Prof. Peebles on what qualities helped him in his career #NobelPrize
#NobelPrize laureate James Peebles arriving on campus to applause by friends and colleagues and a congratulatory greeting by department chair and physics professor Herman Verlinde.

"You don't go into this for the prizes but when they happen, they're fun." Prof. Peebles starts his day on campus after learning he has won the 2019 @NobelPrize in Physics. #NobelPrize – at Jadwin Hall - Dept. Of Physics

"Jim Peebles exemplifies both #PrincetonU’s dazzling tradition of fundamental research in cosmology and gravitation, and also this University’s commitment to put its best scholars in the classroom." — President Eisgruber on #NobelPrize winner Jim Peebles
Prof. Peebles speaks with @NobelPrize about his work as a cosmologist and explorer. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwhoyYpncns #NobelPrize

“When I started working in this subject — I can tell you the date, 1964 — at the invitation of my mentor, Prof. Robert Henry Dicke, I was very uneasy about going into this subject ... I just kept going” Peebles said during the #NobelPrize news conference

"This ceremony and the magnificent artwork we dedicate today are important steps in Princeton’s continuing efforts to speak honestly and completely about its history as we work to build a more fully inclusive campus." Pres. Eisgruber on the installation of "Double Sights"

"I wish my university had half" of what #PrincetonU has done in diversity & inclusion, says Hood, and that when people in the future look back, "I hope that they see that this is the birth" of a transformation. #TigersThrive19

On the piece, Hood says, "Everybody should look at it, experience it, and if you feel like it's not doing enough, keep asking ... You should not settle. We cannot settle." "If we ever stop talking about Woodrow Wilson, we have failed," says Minter. #TigersThrive19
Hood went around the country to see how other colleges have handled similar installations. "Our history is so complex, I don't think there is a singularity" for how it's handled. #TigersThrive19
"I hope we can continue to look at this figure [Woodrow Wilson] in a critical way." #TigersThrive19

Walter Hood says "Double Sights" was "one of the most difficult projects" of his career. He adds, "It's a spacial piece - it's not a monument" and it "forces us to have a conversation." #TigersThrive19

"Student have an important role in this. They have been a part of every committee," says Minter. She adds, "We have much more work to do ... I hope that all of you continue to watch for opportunity. I want you to weigh in." #TigersThrive19

Minter talks about the recent portrait unveiling (https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/09/25/four-new-portraits-serve-visible-expression-princeton-today) and renaming of Rivers Way (https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/04/09/campus-roadway-will-be-named-pioneering-african-american-alumnus-and-princeton) as examples of the positive changes happening at #PrincetonU. #TigersThrive19

"Change comes when it is structural and when there is accountability." Michele Minter, Vice Provost for Institutional Equity and Diversity on the #PrincetonU committees created to make change and diversify campus #TigersThrive19
In deciding to establish "Double Sights," Henry says the committee's thought was, "We ought to make sure everyone understands the complicated legacy of Woodrow Wilson." #TigersThrive19

Brent Henry '69 begins the session with introductions. Henry, a University Trustee, chaired the Wilson Legacy Review Committee, whose recommendations led to the creation of “Double Sights." #TigersThrive19

Measuring 39 feet in height, “Double Sights" is a vertical sculpture of two columnar elements with quotations representing both the positive and negative aspects of Wilson’s legacy. https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/09/24/university-mark-completion-woodrow-wilson-installation-public-discussion-dedication #TigersThrive19

The "Wrestling With History: Expanding Princeton's Historical Narrative and Sense of Place" session features Michele Minter, Vice Provost for Institutional Equity and Diversity and Walter Hood, the artist (& @macfound Fellow) who created "Double Sights." #TigersThrive19

Last but not least, @selwynhinds '93 gives us a teaser on his next big project ... "The movie I'm writing involves a fictional city, the first letter begins with a G" and the story is "known for a nighttime animal." #TigersThrive19

On keeping up with the industry, Johnson says, "Because we're financing shows and movies, we have to keep up with what's resonating ... it's critically important to know what's on, what's working and what's not." #TigersThrive19

As a creator, how do you keep up with your industry and manage your time? @selwynhinds: "I don't. I march to my own muse. I don't care who's doing 'x' and 'y' because I'm doing 'z' ... my fan hat and writer hat are separated." #TigersThrive19

Will people still go to the movie theatre in 5 years? "That's something at @AlconEnt we talk about a lot ... I think there's always going to be a place for the theatrical experience," due to the social, gathering nature of it, says Johnson. #TigersThrive19

"My daughter essentially saved my career," says @selwynhinds. When he was struggling, his daughter fed him the advice he has fed her in tough times ... a few months later, he booked his first major TV gig. #TigersThrive19

"It's the randomness and the psychological part ... the muscles that you have to build ... Princeton helped me with that." @selwynhinds talks about handling the frustrations of the entertainment industry #TigersThrive19

"The industry is going through an immense change ... in that change, here's a lot of opportunity for people of color to participate in creating content." Johnson talks about the increase in streaming platforms and the merging of major entertainment companies #TigersThrive19
"There's a real renaissance for people of color in entertainment. Right now," says Johnson, but, "there needs to be more of a pipeline," to hire them. #TigersThrive19

"Princeton has been pivotal to me and my life in general. Period ... I formed some of my best friendships and enduring relationships here ... It intrigued me how I could combine creativity and finance." Johnson on #PrincetonU's influence on his career #TigersThrive19

"I jump off of cliffs. I see a cliff and say, 'I'm gonna run right off of it and figure out the parachute after.'" @selwynhinds says this thought during his time at #PrincetonU and onward has pushed along his career. #TigersThrive19
The luncheon discussion features @selwynhinds '93 and @AlconEnt Co-CEO Broderick Johnson '90, talking about their roles as pioneers in the film industry. #TigersThrive19

Eric Plummer '10 thanks the panelists and highlights the last discussion saying, "At the end of the day, what #PrincetonU taught you was how to learn, how to fight and how to know where you belong." #TigersThrive19

What did #PrincetonU teach you? Williams '93 says, "We are very special, and we know how to do things, and we are not afraid to do the things that are hard." @ToniTWhitley '85 learned to take on big problems & "In the nation's service" influenced her decisions. #TigersThrive19

"I learned so much by cracking open books," says Dale Williams '93, who follows up Yamusah '13 in saying that there are resources available to teach you what you need to know in the tech fields. #TigersThrive19

What sort of advice do you have for those developing their tech careers? Amina Yamusah ’13 says, "The beauty of technology is open source code," and notes there are many free, online resources to teach yourself tech skills. #TigersThrive19
"We need broader thinking ... we need data science ... we need to make sure our communities are reflected in those core competencies." @ToniTWhitley #TigersThrive19

"There's still that challenge of people, even right now, who have these skills but aren't getting past biased technical hiring screens ... there needs to be more accountability," says Amina Yamusah '13 #TigersThrive19

How do we make tech "cool?" "When you look at things like esports, that's quite a development ... when you're able to bring together things that people love, and show that tech drives it ... that's a win." @gameofgrow #TigersThrive19

"If I'm not polite to Alexa, I get a little concerned," jokes Williams, but notes that as we get more and more devices connected to our in-home networks, we need to be aware that this increases vulnerabilities. #TigersThrive19

As she serves on the @Microsoft AI and Ethics in Engineering and Research Committee, @ToniTWhitley says that, with the customers she works with, "we're using #AI in ways that create inductive unknowns." #TigersThrive19

"For me ... we're that generation that, we started with black and white TV and we've seen it since the beginning and all the way through ... I fell right into it." Dale Williams '93 has always been interested in tech & he'd end up in the industry no matter what #TigersThrive19

"I came into tech asking, 'What could tech do for society?'" With a nod to @BradSmi '83's new book #ToolsAndWeapons, @ToniTWhitley says "It's both of those themes that keep me engaged in this topic." #TigersThrive19

"It's amazing that it connects the whole world ... I find that fascinating. I find that powerful." -@gameofgrow "In order to fight against the machine, you have to build the machine." -Amina Yamusah @princetonalumni answer why they work in the #tech industries #TigersThrive19

The "Tigers in Tech" panel this morning will explore what it means to be a person of color in technology. Moderator: Eric Plummer '10 Speakers: Muoyo Okome '05 (@gameofgrow) Toni Townes-Whitley ’85 (@ToniTWhitley) Dale Williams '93 Amina Yamusah '13 #TigersThrive19

Evora Thomas ’74, Ivy Thomas McKinney ’77 and Daphne Thomas Jones ’77 were among #PrincetonU’s first undergraduate classes that included women. They are proud to say they are the first three sisters to attend the University together. #TigersThrive19
A surprise message from @MichelleObama '85, @princetonalumni reuniting, a dedication at @PULibrary - all this and more! Here's the recap from Day 2 of #TigersThrive19.

On the history of African American Studies, prof. @imaniperry says, "We have figured out a balance between the early energy of understanding black studies as having an immediate and direct connection" with the world we occupy as well as how we got here. #TigersThrive19
"Some will be deeply scholarly while others will be more easily digestible," but, @imaniperry says, "somebody has to be there" to provide the facts. #TigersThrive19

Wrapping things up with audience questions, @esglaude, @KeeangaYamahtta and @imaniperry emphasize the importance of African American Studies as a field as well as the importance of @PrincetonAAS here at #PrincetonU. #TigersThrive19 – at Carl Fields Center/Community House

"There are consequences when we think we're just talking about personal experiences .. because anyone can do it." @KeeangaYamahtta notes that personal stories are important but they also have to be weighted. #TigersThrive19
"Where is the role of the African American Studies scholar in relation to the public?" @esglaude asks about what happens when public-facing figures are named experts in black studies.

"African American Studies exemplifies the best of what you can do in scholarship," says @PrincetonAAS prof. @imaniperry, as the field requires participants to go beyond the standards of other academic subjects. #TigersThrive19
"The need for African American studies has never been greater," says @PrincetonAAS asst. prof. @KeeangaYamahtta. #TigersThrive19
"I have the best colleagues on the planet," says @esglaude in introducing fellow faculty members @imaniperry & @KeeangaYamahtta, each who are award-winning authors as well. #TigersThrive19

This afternoon we’re live from “Looking Back, Moving Forward: 50 Years of African American Studies at Princeton and 10th Anniversary of the Carl A. Fields Center Celebration” with @PrincetonAAS faculty members @esglaude *97, @KeeangaYamahtta and @ImaniPerry. #TigersThrive19

A portrait of Robert Rivers '53 was recently added to the University’s permanent art collection. "My portrait, with my story, is a part of #PrincetonU’s story, and I enjoy the changes that have taken place during my long Princeton journey" http://ow.ly/Jw8M50wC65Q #TigersThrive19

Prof. Sandweiss and @MelanieLawson13 '76 discuss the project and its impact on #PrincetonU. For more information on the #PrincetonAndSlavery Project and its findings, visit: https://slavery.princeton.edu #TigersThrive19

The next #TigersThrive19 session is on #PrincetonAndSlavery Project, with speakers history professor Martha (Marni) Sandweiss, who founded the project, and @MelanieLawson13 '76. Lawson calls the project's work "groundbreaking" and says this morning is "an important moment."

"…because if there's one thing that I've learned since I've left Princeton, it's this: No matter what direction you're headed, nobody gets there alone" @MichelleObama '85 shares a surprise welcome message at #TigersThrive19, a conference celebrating #PrincetonU’s black alumni.

"I'm so grateful for you coming together .. thank you for supporting and engaging with Princeton University." Pres. Eisgruber wraps up his remarks by reflecting on the life of Toni Morrison and emphasizing that we should cherish our time together this weekend #TigersThrive19

"At least 60% of students take at least one @PrincetonCS class during their time at #PrincetonU." Pres. Eisgruber notes that Computer Science has become the #1 major at Princeton. #TigersThrive19

Wrapping up the panel statements is assoc. prof. Sigrid Adriaenssens, who says, "Your advisors are going to be supportive and they are going to be caring, but they are also going to be busy ... what that means is that you're in charge of your education."

Next up is @PrincetonGrad student Lindsay Griffiths. "When I got here, it was like walking into Narnia ... being here felt very intimidating ... but, I want to reiterate: your department believes you belong here, @PrincetonGrad believes you belong here."

"You need to build a community here," says @PrincetonGrad student Noah Apthorpe. He then gives the audience an immediate assignment: turn to the person next to you, introduce yourself find a time to hang out, and put it in your calendar.

"Have something else to do other than your dissertation or that project you're working on." Advice from prof. @KrisRamsay1 to @PrincetonGrad includes focusing on your health and giving yourself a way to step back

Lisa Schreyer, the @PrincetonGrad associate dean for student life, focuses on 3 main points for the audience: : There is life outside your department. : Care for yourself and your community. : We are here for you ... and we want you to succeed.

"I'm excited help all of you envision your future with clarity and confidence as you begin your professional careers at Princeton." Eva Kubu, assoc. dean for professional development, provides info on #profdev resources for @PrincetonGrad

Renita Miller, associate dean for access, diversity and inclusion, notes, "The work that my team does creates and supports efforts to make sure" there's more diversity in the room. "Where you have challenges, it is our responsibility to support you."

"We can help you in several ways with you budget and financial planning." Mary Bechler, senior associate dean for finance and administration, lets @PrincetonGrad know that #PrincetonU is working to empower students and equip them to reduce anxiety about finances.
Cole Crittenden introduces the panel for this morning's program, highlighting the many resources available to @PrincetonGrad students, inside and out of the classroom.
"You absolute have what it takes. We believe in each and every one of you ... We can't wait to see where this path is going to lead you, so, welcome to #PrincetonU!"

"It's okay to feel that you don't have what it takes - as long as you realize that just because you feel that way, doesn't mean that you don't have what it takes ... it means that you're human, and it means that you're a @PrincetonGrad student."

"Some number of years ago I was sitting where you are sitting right now, thinking 'What have I gotten myself into?' ... Over years, you'll all become pioneers in pushing the boundaries of what we already know." @PrincetonGrad Dean Sarah-Jane Leslie *07 addresses the audience.

"Solutions are going to come from students like you." Referencing the #Princeton2023 Pre-Read and last night's discussion with @WilliamsJames_, Pres. Eisgruber points to @PrincetonGrad students to help solve challenges brought on by technology.

"This is, by many metrics, the most diverse group of graduate students matriculated here at #PrincetonU." Pres. Eisgruber kicks off @PrincetonGrad Orientation this morning at Richardson by noting that by diversifying grad students, we can diversify faculties around the country.

"Technology has to be part of the solution to all of this." @WilliamsJames_ responds to @jrexnet and @SamWangPhD and gets ready for student questions. Be sure to catch the livestream to see what students ask: http://mediacentrallive.princeton.edu
"I encourage you to harness that technology to shine the light in dark places." @jrexnet tells #Princeton2023 to "fight fire with fire" and use technologies to make them better

"I implore you to take notes by hand. My research is focused on the internet and I still do this ... please trust me, just do it." On attention and focus, @jrexnet provides some advice to #Princeton2023

"This book hits on key issues that are already affecting your personal lives ... the significance will grow." @jrexnet says while she doesn't agree with anything, she knows that "this really matters."
Now it's time for @jrexnet to provide her thoughts on the book. "I decided to read this as a hard copy, not a kindle."
Quick note: @SamWangPhD gave props to #Princeton2023, noting how little students have been interacting with their devices this evening
"Think of 'Mean Girls' but with spears ... that's how we've evolved." @SamWangPhD gives a brief history on social group size through time

"A book is an inanimate object, but when we read them, we bring to it what we already know and what we think ... what I brought to this book is that the brain has limits and technology is challenging these limits." @SamWangPhD provides his response to the Pre-Read

Some advice for #Princeton2023 using technologies in their education from @WilliamsJames_: "My recommendation would be ... lean into the nuances. There are a lot of false binaries out there ... it's easy to focus on the negatives ... I encourage you to focus on the positives."
With a reference to the Wizard of Oz, @WilliamsJames_ says, "We have a lot of good people working in technology ... but a lot of bad wizards."
Part of why he wrote the book, says @WilliamsJames_, was to "deepen our sense of what's at stake ... what we give our attention to is what we are."

"There are so many spokes off this issue, there's so much to say ... but basically ... digital technologies produced unprecented information abundance, which made attention a scarce resource." @WilliamsJames_ on the core thoughts of the #Princeton2023 Pre-Read

"Everyone likes to think that they're living in the most crucial moment in human history ... the baton you're being passed is kind of an awkward and heavy baton ... It's a crisis of meaning, of attention of focus." @WilliamsJames_ on the existential crises we are living in

"We know that you will infuse living energy into this place from, as Toni Morrison said, many neighborhoods and many lands. We know, too, that wherever you come from, each of you belongs here. We are delighted to see you, and we take great joy in saying, 'Welcome to Princeton!'"

"I hope that your time here will often be exhilarating, but I know that it will not always be easy. That’s more than okay; it is essential. You cannot really learn or grow if everything is always comfortable."
" ... And, we must be willing to reassess our beliefs when confronted with persuasive evidence or arguments that point in new directions."
"We must have the courage to state opinions even when they are unpopular in our community. We must have the integrity to respect those who offer opinions that are unpopular with us."

"I quoted Professor Morrison’s observation about the importance of 'encounters and collaborations' with people from 'other neighborhoods' and 'other lands.' To that list, one might add encounters and collaborations with fundamentally different perspectives and opinions."

"However important it may be to dissent from unjust exercises of power, Morrison’s idea of 'dissent from orthodoxy' runs deeper than that. It requires each of us to interrogate and challenge our own orthodoxies. Dissent, she said, cannot be merely a matter of style or fashion."

Pres. Eisgruber notes Morrison may even have anticipated questions about digital media, as referenced in the #Princeton2023 Pre-Read in asking if 'instruction [would] be executed solely in solitude by the isolated handling of sophisticated new machines.'"

In her essay “The Place of the Idea; the Idea of the Place," says Pres. Eisgruber, "She reminded her listeners, ... that 'Princeton’s mission depended upon “encounters and collaborations among and between strangers from other neighborhoods and strangers from other lands.'"

"Her influence will endure for generations, her name inscribed upon the campus and her voice speaking eloquently from the past to the present. She is at once part of our traditions, and also a potential guide for you as you consider your own relationship to those traditions."

"As we begin this particular year, I find myself contemplating the insight and achievements of one person who had a very special role in this community for thirty years but is no longer with us as we begin this academic year. I am speaking of Toni Morrison."

"... We also recognize that Opening Exercises are a moment for reflection about our University’s mission, the challenges that lie ahead, and the changes occurring within our community and around it." #Princeton2023

Morrison Hall was dedicated in 2017, with President Eisgruber stating, "Toni Morrison's name becomes part of the lexicon through which students, faculty, staff and alumni navigate this campus." https://www.princeton.edu/news/2017/11/20/princeton-dedicates-morrison-hall-honor-nobel-laureate-and-emeritus-faculty-member

Morrison’s arrival helped to attract other faculty and students from traditionally underrepresented backgrounds to #PrincetonU. Two courses this spring allowed students to learn from her works. https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/05/10/reading-toni-morrison-students-explore-princetons-literary-icon-archive-page

Morrison’s novels have been translated into at least 20 languages. Her groundbreaking novels include “The Bluest Eye,” (1970), “Song of Solomon” (1977), “Jazz” (1992), “Home” (2012) and her latest, “The Source of Self-Regard: Selected Essays, Speeches, and Meditations” (2019).
Morrison became the first African American to be awarded the @NobelPrize in Literature (1993) and was also awarded a @PulitzerPrizes for “Beloved” in 1988.
Morrison joined the #PrincetonU faculty in 1989 and was a member of the creative writing program until she transferred to emeritus status in 2006.
We’re celebrating the life and legacy of Toni Morrison through her words, career accomplishments and thoughts from around the world.

"They can stop one of us ... they can't stop all of us!" Thanks to @ambertamblyn for coming to #PrincetonU to chat with @WilsonSchool prof. @julianzelizer about her book "Era of Ignition," @TIMESUPNOW, #MeToo and more.

Why did @ambertamblyn write a letter to her daughter in the book? "I wanted to tell her the truth ... not a veiled version of the truth ... I don't want fairytales anymore. I want our real stories to shine through."
"I think it's a proactive look on how each of us can harness our anger ... and put it out in the world in ways that can forge the change." @ambertamblyn on her latest book, "Era of Ignition"

The @TIMESUPNOW founders started conversations among themselves that made "the most liberal, woke, feminist" women realize they were not necessarily fighting for all of their more marginalized sisters, says @ambertamblyn.

"We're now taking control of the situation and we are going to create change." @TIMESUPNOW was started in part by @ambertamblyn and the "seed" came from her friend @AmericaFerrera who brought up an open letter signed by 700K female farm workers (http://time.com/5018813/farmworkers-solidarity-hollywood-sexual-assault/)

"The abuse of power is such a pervasive problem in any industry ... the band-aid was ripped off ... it's not going to be easy, but what revolution is?" @ambertamblyn on the 2017 #MeToo movement, originally started by @TaranaBurke in 2006

Having written an op-ed entitled "I'm done with not being believed," @ambertamblyn was not only speaking about her own experience but what plenty of women had gone through. She wanted to speak publicly about it to "burst a dam open."

"It was really a powerful day ... I've never experienced anything like it. I was so charged by the experience that march, that when I went back to NY that night, and the NYC march was still going on, I joined that one, too." @ambertamblyn on the @womensmarch in Jan. 2017
On the topic of "locker room talk," @ambertamblyn says, "Words are very deeply tied to actions."
"Seeing women in positions of power can be as important as policy. Actually seeing yourself there does wonders for us." @ambertamblyn

"We have to be honest about the ways in which we have been marginalized ... we need to examine what works still needs to be done." @ambertamblyn on wide-spread sexism

"The @womensmarch and the subsequent anger we felt [after the 2016 election] as a community was, in part, of the election, but more because women really saw, on a large scale, of the rejection of a capable woman." @ambertamblyn's feelings on the reaction to the 2016 election
"So much of what we're feeling, the uncertainty ... I make an argument in the book that we need to lean into these things." @ambertamblyn on how she views current issues and change.
On her film "Paint It Black," @ambertamblyn notes, "I wanted to know what it felt like to have ownership of my own creative visions."

"The image of fire always comes to mind ... this feeling of being ignited ... a term to describe where we are right now," says @ambertamblyn on her book "The Era of Ignition" and where the name came from.

"Everyone has challenges in life — some are just more visible than others. If I can leave you with only one thing, it’s this: Remember everyone you meet is fighting a battle you know nothing about. Be kind. Always.”

Once home from rehab, without distraction, Thomas hit his rock bottom. "After a lot of soul-searching while on those rocks at the bottom, I found my new purpose in life: to help others and have fun doing it.”

"I then spent two months in inpatient rehab. The reframing process post-paralysis has similarities to grieving after losing a loved one. My ‘denial’ stage was to beat the medical community.” It was then that Thomas decided to concentrate his career on neuroscience.

Follow along with the rest of the day's panels and discussions by watching the livestream, checking in on #AIethics and #AIHumanRights and giving @PrincetonCITP a follow. Watch here: http://mediacentrallive.princeton.edu

"Redistribution of rights needs to be at the core," says @ScarletWillcock of @UOW, noting that there are little-to-no privacy rights for those who utilize social welfare programs. #aiethics #aihumanrights

"Given a lot of the complexities around #AI ... I think there are a lot of benefits to a #humanrights approach. Human rights are universal ... they also come with a strong and capable community," explains @hibahsays of @google. #aiethics #aihumanrights

Next up is #PrincetonU's own prof. @MFleurbaey, who says, "If we talk about futuristic technologies, we should also, at the same time, talk about futuristic institutions and societies ... we need to connect #AI with the real needs of society." #AIethics #AIhumanrights

Each panelist has 5 minutes to provide their thoughts. @PopTechWorks of @ualbany says "We have a tendency to talk about these tools as if they are disruptors ... tools are much more evolution than revolution." #aiethics #aihumanrights

Moderating the first panel, "The Human Right to Social Protection," is @cpjvanveen who explains that the panel will cover a multitude of factors including "what are the historical and political contextual factors that influence the introduction of these technologies." #aiethics

"You're the ones who are going to need social protection," at some point, says @Alston_UNSR, emphasizing that, when thinking about #AIethics and #AIHumanRights, you should put yourself in those shoes.

"As soon as we get into the field of social protection, there is an overwhelming sense of the negative," says @Alston_UNSR. We talk about reducing the number of those who need the programs instead of focusing on what they need and improving that. #aiethics #aihumanrights

"Human rights is almost always acknowledged when we start talking about the principles that should govern #AI," says @Alston_UNSR, but it's just mentioned and then quickly passed over. #AIEthics #AIHumanRights

"It's very interesting to think about welfare in the U.S. as part of the social protection issue. What is welfare in the U.S.? Food stamps, housing assistance, Medicaid ...Once you add this up ... it's tens of millions of Americans." @Alston_UNSR #aiethics #aihumanrights

"There isn't a clear definition of it. We want to avoid a reference to welfare ... if we think about it logically, it embraces all of us." @Alston_UNSR on the term "social protection" when it comes to #AIHumanRights and #AIethics.
Delivering a framing speech for today's conference is @Alston_UNSR, who is collecting data throughout the day to contribute to his @UN General Assembly report on #AIHumanRights and #AIEthics issues.

"Whether you're on the technical or policy side of this [#AI] border, it's important to be thinking about what you can do to enable practitioners on the other side" to do their job more efficiently, says @EdFelten as he wraps up opening remarks. #aiethics #aihumanrights

When it comes to social welfare, #AI helps social scientists better understand social ills like poverty, leading to improvements in social protection. Further, it leads to more effective decision-making, so programs better support social improvement and human rights. #AIethics
What has changed since Turing's time? A focus on narrow #AI (measurable, cognitive tasks), optimizing measures of performance and statistics-driven methods. #AIethics #AIhumanrights

In talking about the history of #AI, @EdFelten references Alan Turing *38, saying that he had the "best opening" to a paper ever: "I propose to answer the question: can machines think?" #AIethics #AIhumanrights

Why has #machinelearning become so prominent? @EdFelten says, "The surge in progress has come as a surprise to people ... the idea is that the technology has reached a turning point." #AIethics #AIhumanrights

"From the stand point of applications on social protection," says @EdFelten, "we're really looking at supervised learning" learning from examples)in two categories: predictive analytics and classification. #AIethics #AIHumanRights
Director of @PrincetonCITP and @PrincetonCS prof. @EdFelten kicks things off by defining #AI and #machinelearning. #aiethics #aihumanrights
This morning, we'll be joining @PrincetonCITP at their conference co-organized with @Alston_UNSR that focuses on human rights in the digital age. Follow along here and with #AIethics.

"Your battle is the battle for truth ... You have the intellect, the time and the idealism to fight this." @mariaressa on what #PrincetonU can do to shine the light and fight for #humanrights, #holdtheline and #defendpressfreedom.
"I have great faith that, in the end, we're on the right side of history." @mariaressa on why she continues to #HoldTheLine and #DefendPressFreedom.

"I've never used micro-targeting because that kind of manipulation, to me, feels unethical ... what's wrong with technology today is that there has to be transparency to you can be consistent and accountable." @mariaressa on strategies that spread #fakenews
"What you do today will shape what journalism looks like in the future." @mariaressa '86 talks with @tweber '89 on what current students in journalism can expect years from now.
"Make the choice to learn," is @mariaressa's advice for life after #PrincetonU.

"What #PrincetonU taught me is that whatever mess the world is in ... pull a thread, and pull that thread with great persistence until you have clarity of thought. What Princeton taught me is how to solve a problem." @mariaressa '86
"I was pre-med ... and then I did English and theater and dance ... I fell into journalism." @mariaressa on her #PrincetonU experience and how she became a reporter.
"I'm reminded of how fortunate we are to have people like you," says @tweber '89, of @mariaressa's work as a journalist despite going through dangerous situations.
"How do we stand up? You have to start with your area of influence." @mariaressa explains that she encourages students and others to #DefendPressFreedom and #HoldTheLine.
When it comes to trolls and hatred online, @mariaressa says to "choose your battles."
"When you don't have truth, you don't have trust." @mariaressa '86 explains how the spread of #fakenews has weakened the public's trust in news media.
At one point, @mariaressa was receiving 90 hate messages per hour. "It's not just fake accounts, but real people, and you can't tell the difference."
Sometimes as a journalist, the only defense is to "shine a light," says @mariaressa.
Defining "patriotic trolling," @mariaressa explains state-sponsored hate propaganda and how it spreads.
To kick off the talk, @mariaressa shows a video about her company @rapplerdotcom and the "battle for truth."
"It doesn't change," says @mariaressa about the look of #PrincetonU's campus and what's it like to be back.

"We talked about family, we talked about politics in sport, we talked about politics in race ... now, it's important we talk about you. One thing that jumped off the page was that you refuse to be boxed in." @esglaude on @mosesbread72
On taking a knee, @mosesbread72 says, "We're really honoring the people who came before us ... it became not only about police brutality but about everything that was going on in America."
"There's so many kids that are looking up to us at this moment ... I think it's really important as an athlete to push that agenda." @mosesbread72 on using the platform of celebrity for public good

"When it comes to integration in sports ... we think because there's black players on the field, that there's integration. But we need integration in the board rooms. And it's not just black and white ...for women, we need to have opportunities." @mosesbread72
"I want people to understand the fullness of who you are," says @esglaude on tonight's discussion.
"There's people in the NFL or who have retired that don't know themselves ... everyone's dependent on the athlete" instead of "the person." @mosesbread72
Having played football together at every level, @mosesbread72 and @MartysaurusRex easily understand each other and talk to each other around five times a day. "He's my best friend."

"My mom is a different dynamic ... she's a very strong woman. She's a teacher, so everything growing up for me was about education." @mosesbread72 on his mother playing a role in his work ethic and identity

Talking about his father, @mosesbread72 says, "Through his story, he said 'Stay there.' At the end of the day, you have to be there for your family ... He really shaped me as a man." Pictured here is Michael alongside Michael Bennett Sr.

Michael tells the story of growing up in Louisiana, working on a farm with his grandparents. His grandfather was fixing a tractor when it started to fall on top of him. @mosesbread72 caught the tractor and saved his grandfather and thought "... Yeah, I'm going to the @NFL."
Will his brother @MartysaurusRex come out of retirement to play with @mosesbread72? It'd be great, but, it's probably "fake news," says Bennett.

"There's a lot of moving pieces to it ... I get to be with one of the brightest minds in football, ever, with Bill Belichick." @mosesbread72 on, as @esglaude called "the elephant in the room," his very recent trade to the @Patriots.

We're at Richardson Auditorium as activist, author & @NFL player @mosesbread72 joins #PrincetonU prof. @esglaude in a discussion entitled "Race & the NFL." Earlier, Bennett met with faculty, staff and students, chatting about his work ethic and his efforts outside of football.

Finally, the students collaborated to create a fight scene using the moves they learned. Here's the final product!
Whoever rolled, picked up their object and then pointed first was the winner of each round -- check it out in slow motion!
The last move the students learned was rolling: forward, backward and even how to pick up objects along the way -- all in one fluid motion.

Turn the sound on this quick video to hear the students performing "knaps." For this move, Minjae says the important thing is to cup your hand instead of making a fist -- because in that case, you're just punching yourself.
Once students were comfortable with the motion of punching, then came the sound. "Knaps" are the sounds that actors make using their foot or hand to make hits have a loud sound.

Then, the students learned how to do some punches, using not just their fists but their entire bodies. On stage, as Minjae explained, you've got to make punches look as if they land much harder than they actually would.

The first task was learning how to fall. Minjae noted that when it comes to stage combat, "If you can't do it 100 times a day, don't do it. It isn't sustainable." So, if falling a lot during a scene will make you tired after rehearsing it over and over, change things up!

Wrapping up her @PrincetonDH Year of Data keynote address in front of a standing-room-only crowd, @safiyanoble says, "We have more data and technology than ever, and more social, political and economic inequality and injustice go with it." #CDHYODA
"An app will not save us. We will not sort out social inequality lying in bed staring at smartphones." @safiyanoble shares a portion of her book, which you can read here via @Wired #CDHYODA

When it comes to search engines, @safiyanoble notes, "it might be great for finding out if Starbucks is across the street," but if you start asking deeper, social questions, "you get a whole different set of conversations." #CDHYODA

"We're so concerned with the momentary dimensions ... that we're not thinking about how these platforms are being manipulated" in the long term, despite various hate groups having "100-year plans." @safiyanoble on the need for being literate in this field #CDHYODA

When a major bias incident occurs, a common response from a representative is that the company does not control searches and that everything is essentially automatic. "If Google is not in charge of their own results," @safiyanoble asks jokingly, "then, who is in charge?" #CDHYODA

"It's just insincere and disingenuous to tell the public that they should be more savvy and know better ... after years of being acculturated to look for banal things," @safiyanoble says that simple & easy but important things should be simple & easy to find. #CDHYODA

When talking about how the 2016 election brought algorithms into major headlines around the country, @safiyanoble notes that there are certainly those that believe "search engines can pose a real threat to our democratic system of government." #CDHYODA

"One of the challenges of interdisciplinary work ... it kind of means you have to speak 5 languages instead of 1 ... but that work is really important if we're going to have the interventions we want to see." @safiyanoble on working across industries #CDHYODA

With past experience in the advertising industry, when @safiyanoble started her research, she knew ways to get on the first page of @google. So, she knew these tactics could be manipulated by those who have the most money -- and that these searches are often biased. #CDHYODA
What's @safiyanoble's number one tip to teachers & parents? "Stop telling your students just to @Google things." #CDHYODA

In 2012, the idea of bias within coding and algorithms was unheard of. "It's starting to become common knowledge that ... operating systems can discriminate." @safiyanoble on the growth of this idea in just a few years #CDHYODA

"Digital failures are often communicated [by saying] there's a glitch in an otherwise perfect operating system ... hoping to gather enough evidence that there's a little more than a glitch at play." @safiyanoble on common Silicon Valley explanations for major mistakes #CDHYODA

"Algorithms have been in the headlines for the last year or so in a different way than they had been before ... in 2013 my editor said, 'No one knows what an algorithm is.'" @safiyanoble on naming her book "Algorithms of Oppression." #CDHYODA

Associate professor of @PrincetonAAS Ruha Benjamin (@ruha9) introduces @safiyanoble with tales of "phone spying" and how younger generations are learning things on their own, without the use of screens. #CDHYODA
The talk this evening is entitled "Algorithms of Oppression: How Search Engines Reinforce Racism." @safiyanoble is an assistant professor at @USCAnnenberg. #CDHYODA
We're here at 010 East Pyne for the @PrincetonDH Year of Data keynote lecture with @safiyanoble. Stay tuned to our timeline for updates throughout the talk and follow along with #CDHYODA.

Wrapping up tonight's event, @billmckibben answers a question from an 11-year-old audience member: "People who seemingly have not much power, in fact, can play an enormous role in making things change ... there's absolute no age limit in making that happen."

"People should definitely build movements and we'll give them all of the advice and support we can!" @billmckibben says his @350 organization is ready and willing to help those in the #climatechange fight.
Should we have a carbon tax? @billmckibben explains, "There should be no reason to let everybody pour carbon into the atmosphere for free. We don't do that with anything else."

"If we really wanted to make the all-out effort to do this [replace oil] ... we could make that transition ... 75 years from now, the world will run on wind and sun." @billmckibben sits down for an audience Q&A.
To wrap up, @billmckibben emphasizes, "Everyone, including artists, is called to citizenship and solidarity. We cannot win this fight as individuals."
With a shoutout to "kayak-tivists," @billmckibben says that "we are leaving behind a visual record of that fight."
"There are certain tropes that just kind of click in the human mind .. maybe the simplest and most powerful is the 'many and the small' against 'the big, the powerful, and the few.'" @billmckibben
Civil disobedience, although we don't often think of it as such, is a form of art, says @billmckibben. The images that result are often powerful enough to garner change.
Thirty years ago, #climatechange photos were hard to come by. Now, says @billmckibben? So many come in at such a frequent rate that they're difficult to process and evaluate.

"The world looks remarkably different" than it did when we first gathered images from space decades ago, notes @billmckibben. Further, he says, "If we don't solve this problem now, we will not solve it."

Roughly 15 years ago, @billmckibben asked why there was no art about #climatechange. The answer? Nature was in the background of human-to-human interactions. Since then, and, more recently, it's in the forefront.
"It is a fight that demands all of the resources we can bring to it ... of those resources, art might be the most important." @billmckibben
"It's a fight that demands not just solidarity but it's a fight that demands enormous economic change." @billmckibben on #climatechange
"There is no place untrammeled by any man ... No matter how far you go in this world go, you can't escape its politics ... We are in a fight of immense proportions." @billmckibben
"I remain a romantic, myself, of the American landscape ... conservation, for all its contradictions, should be one of our proudest boasts." @billmckibben
Prof. Michael Oppenheimer (@ClimateOpp) kicks things off with a short bio about @billmckibben and what his legacy means - and what it will mean in years to come.

"This question of 'Who Counts?' becomes evermore important. What does it mean to be evaluated by someone else’s machines? What is reduced? What is lost? The question always comes back to data collection." @thistimeitsmimi on missing data #CDHYoDA

.@thistimeitsmimi gives 4 reasons for missing data sets: those with resources lack incentives, collection takes more than it gives, data resist metrification, and, there are benefits to nonexistence. #CDHYoDA
By collecting missing data sets, @thistimeitsmimi is interested in the pattern behind the data. "Why are these things missing?" #CDHYoDA
Next up is @thistimeitsmimi, speaking on the implications of machine-readable world. "We are being transformed into data objects." #CDHYoDA

"We're all teachers of how structural power operates, and students of it as well ... working together we can really create a field that matters in the future," says @laurenfklein about #digitalhumanities. #CDHYoDA

"Sometimes data collection can have harmful consequences, especially for marginalized groups," says @laurenfklein, who explains that making a visualization including these data sets can bring negative attention. #CDHYoDA

From a data design perspective, @laurenfklein explains that between these two options, the bar chart might be considered "better," but, referring to the bottom visualization, "Why shouldn't a data visualization make us feel something?" #CDHYoDA
.@laurenfklein and her collaborator's data feminism principles include rethinking binaries, making labor visible, and considering context. #CDHYoDA
When it comes to persuasive visualizations, like infographics and maps, @laurenfklein says, "Power also operates in data sciences in products ... whose perspective are we seeing?" #CDHYoDA

With a focused talk on "Data Feminism," @laurenfklein notes that, like feminism, data is about power - who has it, who doesn't, the consequences of each, and how differentials of power can be challenged and changed. #CDHYoDA

.@SamWangPhD wraps up by looking to the future: "The road ahead for us is exciting ... we're hoping to provide help for state-level activists ... our hope is to help provide open data and software" for everybody in the United States.

Existing public and private databases contain many errors due to things like little quality control and lost data. Because of this, @SamWangPhD says, "at some point, it needs to be powered by citizens."

The next step: @SamWangPhD and his team are gathering data about redistricting in 4 states in hopes to expand to all 50 states (along with D.C. and Puerto Rico) by 2021 to eventually achieve open, public access.
"This is the beginning of a long road in which we're going to find out if this approach is going to work," says @SamWangPhD of his team's recent @CommonCause win.
Federal election law, as @SamWangPhD notes, can be compared to the Death Star from @starwars -- "an impregnable fortress."

"Using our statistical measures, there used to be ~1 bad gerrymander per decade ... by the 2010s, 7 were picked up." @SamWangPhD and his team have developed the Princeton Gerrymandering Project to track this info.
"People will go to great lengths to elect voters that are agreeable" to them as candidates.
Attempted fixes to gerrymandering have included: federal courts, state courts and New Federalism. The fundamental problem? The system has to want to be fixed.
.@SamWangPhD says, "Gerrymandering is old, but it's been made new again" due to partisanship.

"The Civil War was a time of racial divisions, technological disruption ... increasing inequality, and deep, deep partisanship." @SamWangPhD notes that we're currently living in a time with all of those factors once again.
"Majority rule does not come easily in our electoral system."

U.S. Supreme Court Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor have much in common. They are among the four women who have served on the high court. They are from New York City. And they both went to #PrincetonU. Here's what they discussed at #SheRoars18.
Highlights from today's conversation with #SCOTUS Justices Sonia Sotomayor '76 and Elena Kagan '81 at #SheRoars18.

"Given the nature of the court, and the fact that we all understand that we're one among nine, and that our votes are equal ... it doesn't affect us as much." - Justice Sotomayor '76 on potentially being interrupted more often than the men on the Supreme Court #SheRoars18

"I actually don't feel a lot of gaps," says Justice Kagan '81 on being one of the first women on the Supreme Court. Further, with 3 women on the Supreme Court, "It seems to me that we don't have to take a backseat role." #SheRoars18
"You have to prove the case, but you have to convince a reader of the moral justice in your decision." - Justice Sotomayor '76 on her dissent style #SheRoars18
"I try to find the good in every person." - Justice Sotomayor '76 explains that there's "more space to talk" when you realize that we all have differences in our opinions. #SheRoars18

"We all get along genuinely ... we believe everyone is operating in good faith around the table. What accounts for that ... is personalities." - Justice Kagan '81 on how #SCOTUS members operate #SheRoars18

"We have to rise above partisanship in our personal relationships. We have to treat each other with respect and dignity and with a sense of amicability that the worst of the world doesn't often share." -Justice Sotomayor '76 #SheRoars18
Hi Cristian, please contact Media Relations at mediarelations@princeton.edu

Justice Kagan '81 explains, "I think it's an extremely important thing for the court ... that over the last 30 years ... there has been a person who people have found in the center. That's enabled the court to look as though it's not all for one side or the other." #SheRoars18

"I think it's important for all of us, for women to understand that no matter how hostile an environment may seem, you have to look around you ... for the people who will stand by you." - Justice Sotomayor '76 #SheRoars18
"Learning is a lifelong endeavor." Further, says Justice Sotomayor '76, sometimes you have to just "jump in" and take chances. #SheRoars18
Justice Kagan '81 credits "serendipity" and being able to change her plans "in a moment's notice" for why she's gone from being a dean to becoming a Supreme Court Justice. #SheRoars18
On making jumps to different jobs, Justice Kagan '81 notes, "the variety of things that I was able to do was really part of the fun of putting together a legal career." #SheRoars18
"I have always looked for those mentors when I enter a workplace that help me understand things ... and can do what I don't think I can do." Justice Sotomayor '76 #SheRoars18
"What counts is coming back and actually implementing those suggestions in a positive way." Justice Sotomayor '76 on listening to your mentors #SheRoars18
"The beauty of a place like Princeton is it let us all march to the beat of our own drummers while being on the same parade route." Justice Sotomayor '76 on fitting in at #PrincetonU #SheRoars18
"I came down here and just fell in love with the place." Justice Kagan '81 on her decision to come to #PrincetonU. #SheRoars18 – at Jadwin Gymnasium

Whetstone considers himself a "concerned artist not looking for solutions, but metaphors" that can help people improve our land. #PEI_Faculty_Seminar

"I feel like I was witnessing something that was very, very ancient while also very, very contemporary." - Whetstone, on his film "The Batture Ritual," which highlights the goings-on of the economy around a particular tree in New Orleans. #PEI_Faculty_Seminar

Faced with the challenges of capturing the visuals of #climatechange as they're happening in real-time, particularly in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina, "I tried to tell the story of how people are adapting to this." #PEI_Faculty_Seminar
When Whetstone looks to shoot, he looks for "land that is interstitial, unowned, and a byproduct of a commodity," which led him to his work along the Mississippi. #PEI_Faculty_Seminar
On areas like Kentucky, where Whetstone once lived, "The landscape forms the people ... The land is instrumental in our perceptions." #PEI_Faculty_Seminar
"What is wild now, and what is wild in the future?" These are the questions Whetstone set out to answer in his works. #PEI_Faculty_Seminar

In comparing early photographers and how they saw and displayed the Western Hemisphere, Whetstone notes, "Early on, photography is an opinion ... and landscape is not something to record, but something to project upon."
For his undergrad career, Whetstone studied zoology. "When I see a landscape ... I see ecological systems. When I see a human ... I see instincts."

Results of Whetstone's involvement with the @PrincetonPEI Urban Grand Challenges program include "Flow: Living with the Mississippi," "The Batture Ritual" and a #PrincetonU class entitled "The Port of New Orleans."
At today's @PrincetonPEI #PEI_Faculty_Seminar, @princetonarts prof. Jeff Whetstone is presenting "The New Wilderness," including some of his works from his documentary of life along the Mississippi.
